</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Villous lesions are advanced adenomas that manifest most commonly in the colon; however, they can develop throughout the gastrointestinal tract. The duodenum is the most common small-bowel site of these lesions. Although in most cases these are isolated lesions that occur sporadically, patients with certain specific colorectal cancer syndromes, including familial adenomatous polyposis and hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer, may develop multiple advanced adenomas. Villous lesions are important because although they are histologically benign, they may harbor dysplasia and have potential for malignancy. These characteristics make them a primary target for colorectal cancer screening with optical and virtual colonoscopy. However, these lesions can also be symptomatic and detected at diagnostic imaging when patients present for examination. They have characteristic features at a variety of imaging examinations, including barium fluoroscopy, CT, MRI, and endoscopic US. It is important for radiologists to be aware of these lesions, their potential morphologies, and their typical appearances at multimodality imaging. Although villous tumors can be detected at imaging and confirmed with biopsy, owing to limitations in identifying dysplasia and foci of malignancy with the above modalities alone and the potential for malignancy, referral for surgical resection of these lesions ultimately is required.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2018</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170159">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170159">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig1.jpeg" height="1644" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Histologic features of villous lesions. Low-power (left) and high-power (right) photomicrographs stained with hematoxylin-eosin show a lobulated or frondlike lesion with long finger-like straight projections, with a disordered columnar epithelium and tubular glands extending from the base of the mucosa.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig2.jpeg" height="1437" width="3200" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Adenoma-to-carcinoma sequence. Diagram illustrates the stepwise transformation that occurs, from normal mucosa, to early adenoma, to late adenoma, to cancer. This progression involves the inactivation of tumor suppressor genes (eg, <i>APC, TP53</i>) and the activation of oncogenes (eg, K-<i>ras, DCC</i>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig3a.jpeg" height="1153" width="1622" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. FAP in a 20-year-old woman. Axial contrast material–enhanced CT image <b>(a)</b>, endoscopic image <b>(b)</b>, and gross surgical specimen <b>(c)</b> show multiple (&gt;100) small polyps carpeting the entire colon.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig3b.jpeg" height="1153" width="1331" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. FAP in a 20-year-old woman. Axial contrast material–enhanced CT image <b>(a)</b>, endoscopic image <b>(b)</b>, and gross surgical specimen <b>(c)</b> show multiple (&gt;100) small polyps carpeting the entire colon.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig3c.jpeg" height="1062" width="1599" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. FAP in a 20-year-old woman. Axial contrast material–enhanced CT image <b>(a)</b>, endoscopic image <b>(b)</b>, and gross surgical specimen <b>(c)</b> show multiple (&gt;100) small polyps carpeting the entire colon.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig4a.jpeg" height="1402" width="1831" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Duodenal villous lesion in a 54-year-old man with FAP who underwent remote colectomy. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT images (<b>b</b> obtained slightly inferior to <b>a</b>) show a carpet lesion (circle) along the second and third portions of the duodenum. <b>(c)</b> Endoscopic and biopsy (not shown) findings confirmed the presence of villous adenoma of the duodenum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig4b.jpeg" height="1402" width="1920" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Duodenal villous lesion in a 54-year-old man with FAP who underwent remote colectomy. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT images (<b>b</b> obtained slightly inferior to <b>a</b>) show a carpet lesion (circle) along the second and third portions of the duodenum. <b>(c)</b> Endoscopic and biopsy (not shown) findings confirmed the presence of villous adenoma of the duodenum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig4c.jpeg" height="1060" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Duodenal villous lesion in a 54-year-old man with FAP who underwent remote colectomy. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT images (<b>b</b> obtained slightly inferior to <b>a</b>) show a carpet lesion (circle) along the second and third portions of the duodenum. <b>(c)</b> Endoscopic and biopsy (not shown) findings confirmed the presence of villous adenoma of the duodenum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig5a.jpeg" height="1161" width="1783" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer (HNPCC) syndrome in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a 33-year-old woman found to have right-sided invasive adenocarcinoma. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial staging CT image <b>(b)</b> in a 59-year-old woman with HNPCC and a recent diagnosis of endometrial cancer shows a large low-attenuating ascending colon cancer. Histopathologic specimen <b>(c)</b>, with immunohistochemical staining for surface markers of mismatch repair gene expression at high magnification, shows loss of expression, which is representative of high microsatellite instability in the colon tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig5b.jpeg" height="1161" width="1963" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer (HNPCC) syndrome in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a 33-year-old woman found to have right-sided invasive adenocarcinoma. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial staging CT image <b>(b)</b> in a 59-year-old woman with HNPCC and a recent diagnosis of endometrial cancer shows a large low-attenuating ascending colon cancer. Histopathologic specimen <b>(c)</b>, with immunohistochemical staining for surface markers of mismatch repair gene expression at high magnification, shows loss of expression, which is representative of high microsatellite instability in the colon tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig5c.jpeg" height="1356" width="1704" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. Hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer (HNPCC) syndrome in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a 33-year-old woman found to have right-sided invasive adenocarcinoma. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial staging CT image <b>(b)</b> in a 59-year-old woman with HNPCC and a recent diagnosis of endometrial cancer shows a large low-attenuating ascending colon cancer. Histopathologic specimen <b>(c)</b>, with immunohistochemical staining for surface markers of mismatch repair gene expression at high magnification, shows loss of expression, which is representative of high microsatellite instability in the colon tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig6.jpeg" height="1594" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. McKittrick-Wheelock syndrome in a 78-year-old man with watery diarrhea. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large sessile polypoid lesion, with a cerebriform appearance and surrounded by fluid, in the rectum. The diagnosis was villous adenoma with McKittrick-Wheelock syndrome.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig7a.jpeg" height="1776" width="1152" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Rectosigmoid lesions. <b>(a)</b> Double-contrast barium enema radiograph obtained in a 61-year-old man shows a lobulated lesion etched in barium in the rectosigmoid colon, with insinuation of barium into the interstices of the lesion in a soap-bubble appearance (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Double-contrast barium enema radiograph obtained in a 59-year-old man shows a similar lobulated lesion, with a slightly feathery margin (arrow), etched in barium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig7b.jpeg" height="1776" width="1317" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Rectosigmoid lesions. <b>(a)</b> Double-contrast barium enema radiograph obtained in a 61-year-old man shows a lobulated lesion etched in barium in the rectosigmoid colon, with insinuation of barium into the interstices of the lesion in a soap-bubble appearance (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Double-contrast barium enema radiograph obtained in a 59-year-old man shows a similar lobulated lesion, with a slightly feathery margin (arrow), etched in barium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig8a.jpeg" height="1299" width="1834" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Duodenal villous lesions. Upper GI images obtained in a 65-year-old man <b>(a)</b> and a 56-year-old man <b>(b)</b> show large lobulated lesions (arrows), with a cauliflower, or soap-bubble, appearance, in the duodenum. As with rectal lesions, there is insinuation of barium into the interstices of these lesions.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig8b.jpeg" height="1289" width="1522" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Duodenal villous lesions. Upper GI images obtained in a 65-year-old man <b>(a)</b> and a 56-year-old man <b>(b)</b> show large lobulated lesions (arrows), with a cauliflower, or soap-bubble, appearance, in the duodenum. As with rectal lesions, there is insinuation of barium into the interstices of these lesions.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig9a.jpeg" height="1602" width="1532" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Villous adenomas at routine CT. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 48-year-old man shows a large lobulated soft-tissue mass (arrow in a) in the cecum; endoscopic findings <b>(b)</b> confirmed the presence of this lesion. Biopsy revealed a villous adenoma, but foci of invasive adenocarcinoma were found at surgical resection. These findings demonstrate the limitations of imaging and biopsy and emphasize why complete resection is required for villous adenomas. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT images obtained in a 66-year-old man who presented with constipation show synchronous colon masses, with an annular adenocarcinoma (arrow in <b>c</b>) in the sigmoid colon and a lobulated villous adenoma (arrow in <b>d</b>) surrounded by fluid in the rectum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig9b.jpeg" height="1602" width="1405" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Villous adenomas at routine CT. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 48-year-old man shows a large lobulated soft-tissue mass (arrow in a) in the cecum; endoscopic findings <b>(b)</b> confirmed the presence of this lesion. Biopsy revealed a villous adenoma, but foci of invasive adenocarcinoma were found at surgical resection. These findings demonstrate the limitations of imaging and biopsy and emphasize why complete resection is required for villous adenomas. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT images obtained in a 66-year-old man who presented with constipation show synchronous colon masses, with an annular adenocarcinoma (arrow in <b>c</b>) in the sigmoid colon and a lobulated villous adenoma (arrow in <b>d</b>) surrounded by fluid in the rectum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig9c.jpeg" height="1363" width="1517" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Villous adenomas at routine CT. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 48-year-old man shows a large lobulated soft-tissue mass (arrow in a) in the cecum; endoscopic findings <b>(b)</b> confirmed the presence of this lesion. Biopsy revealed a villous adenoma, but foci of invasive adenocarcinoma were found at surgical resection. These findings demonstrate the limitations of imaging and biopsy and emphasize why complete resection is required for villous adenomas. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT images obtained in a 66-year-old man who presented with constipation show synchronous colon masses, with an annular adenocarcinoma (arrow in <b>c</b>) in the sigmoid colon and a lobulated villous adenoma (arrow in <b>d</b>) surrounded by fluid in the rectum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig9d.jpeg" height="1363" width="1436" aria-labelledby="fig9d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span>. Villous adenomas at routine CT. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 48-year-old man shows a large lobulated soft-tissue mass (arrow in a) in the cecum; endoscopic findings <b>(b)</b> confirmed the presence of this lesion. Biopsy revealed a villous adenoma, but foci of invasive adenocarcinoma were found at surgical resection. These findings demonstrate the limitations of imaging and biopsy and emphasize why complete resection is required for villous adenomas. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT images obtained in a 66-year-old man who presented with constipation show synchronous colon masses, with an annular adenocarcinoma (arrow in <b>c</b>) in the sigmoid colon and a lobulated villous adenoma (arrow in <b>d</b>) surrounded by fluid in the rectum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig9d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig10a.jpeg" height="1030" width="1081" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Villous lesion seen at CT colonography. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial 3D <b>(a)</b> and 2D <b>(b)</b> CT colonographic images obtained in a 57-year-old man who underwent routine screening show a 3-cm lobulated lesion (arrow) in the cecum. The lesion is coated with contrast material that is extending into the crevices of the lesion <b>(b)</b>. <b>(c)</b> This lesion was confirmed at colonoscopy, and biopsy and resection (not shown) revealed tubulovillous adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig10b.jpeg" height="1345" width="1599" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Villous lesion seen at CT colonography. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial 3D <b>(a)</b> and 2D <b>(b)</b> CT colonographic images obtained in a 57-year-old man who underwent routine screening show a 3-cm lobulated lesion (arrow) in the cecum. The lesion is coated with contrast material that is extending into the crevices of the lesion <b>(b)</b>. <b>(c)</b> This lesion was confirmed at colonoscopy, and biopsy and resection (not shown) revealed tubulovillous adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig10c.jpeg" height="1030" width="1170" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span>. Villous lesion seen at CT colonography. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial 3D <b>(a)</b> and 2D <b>(b)</b> CT colonographic images obtained in a 57-year-old man who underwent routine screening show a 3-cm lobulated lesion (arrow) in the cecum. The lesion is coated with contrast material that is extending into the crevices of the lesion <b>(b)</b>. <b>(c)</b> This lesion was confirmed at colonoscopy, and biopsy and resection (not shown) revealed tubulovillous adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig11a.jpeg" height="1154" width="1164" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Carpet villous lesion in a 50-year-old asymptomatic man who underwent routine colorectal cancer screening. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial 3D CT colonographic image <b>(a)</b> and axial 2D polyp-window <b>(b)</b>and abdominal-window <b>(c)</b> CT colonographic images show a flat lobulated 4-cm carpet lesion (arrow in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) in the cecum. The lesion is large but superficially spreading, relatively flat, and without much bulk. It is best seen on the 3D image <b>(a)</b>, but it could mimic adherent stool. The 2D CT colonographic images <b>(b, c)</b> show contrast material coating the surface of this subtle lesion, which may aid in detection. Unlike in cases of tagged adherent stool, in this case, there is soft tissue undermining the contrast material coating, and this raises concern for a flat or carpet lesion. <b>(d)</b> The carpet villous lesion was confirmed at colonoscopy, and surgical pathologic analysis (not shown) revealed tubulovillous adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig11b.jpeg" height="859" width="1496" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Carpet villous lesion in a 50-year-old asymptomatic man who underwent routine colorectal cancer screening. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial 3D CT colonographic image <b>(a)</b> and axial 2D polyp-window <b>(b)</b>and abdominal-window <b>(c)</b> CT colonographic images show a flat lobulated 4-cm carpet lesion (arrow in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) in the cecum. The lesion is large but superficially spreading, relatively flat, and without much bulk. It is best seen on the 3D image <b>(a)</b>, but it could mimic adherent stool. The 2D CT colonographic images <b>(b, c)</b> show contrast material coating the surface of this subtle lesion, which may aid in detection. Unlike in cases of tagged adherent stool, in this case, there is soft tissue undermining the contrast material coating, and this raises concern for a flat or carpet lesion. <b>(d)</b> The carpet villous lesion was confirmed at colonoscopy, and surgical pathologic analysis (not shown) revealed tubulovillous adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig11c.jpeg" height="859" width="1456" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Carpet villous lesion in a 50-year-old asymptomatic man who underwent routine colorectal cancer screening. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial 3D CT colonographic image <b>(a)</b> and axial 2D polyp-window <b>(b)</b>and abdominal-window <b>(c)</b> CT colonographic images show a flat lobulated 4-cm carpet lesion (arrow in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) in the cecum. The lesion is large but superficially spreading, relatively flat, and without much bulk. It is best seen on the 3D image <b>(a)</b>, but it could mimic adherent stool. The 2D CT colonographic images <b>(b, c)</b> show contrast material coating the surface of this subtle lesion, which may aid in detection. Unlike in cases of tagged adherent stool, in this case, there is soft tissue undermining the contrast material coating, and this raises concern for a flat or carpet lesion. <b>(d)</b> The carpet villous lesion was confirmed at colonoscopy, and surgical pathologic analysis (not shown) revealed tubulovillous adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig11d.jpeg" height="1154" width="1093" aria-labelledby="fig11d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11d</span>. Carpet villous lesion in a 50-year-old asymptomatic man who underwent routine colorectal cancer screening. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial 3D CT colonographic image <b>(a)</b> and axial 2D polyp-window <b>(b)</b>and abdominal-window <b>(c)</b> CT colonographic images show a flat lobulated 4-cm carpet lesion (arrow in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) in the cecum. The lesion is large but superficially spreading, relatively flat, and without much bulk. It is best seen on the 3D image <b>(a)</b>, but it could mimic adherent stool. The 2D CT colonographic images <b>(b, c)</b> show contrast material coating the surface of this subtle lesion, which may aid in detection. Unlike in cases of tagged adherent stool, in this case, there is soft tissue undermining the contrast material coating, and this raises concern for a flat or carpet lesion. <b>(d)</b> The carpet villous lesion was confirmed at colonoscopy, and surgical pathologic analysis (not shown) revealed tubulovillous adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig11d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig12a.jpeg" height="1130" width="954" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Duodenal villous lesions. <b>(a–c)</b> Images obtained in a 59-year-old man with epigastric pain. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a polypoid lesion (arrow) arising near the junction of the second and third portions of the duodenum. The lesion has a heterogeneous lobulated margin, with heterogeneous enhancement and surrounding fluid. The results of esophagogastroduodenoscopy <b>(b)</b> confirmed the findings in a, revealing a large lobulated tumor that was hypoechoic at endoscopic US <b>(c)</b>. Tissue-sampling results confirmed the presence of duodenal villous adenoma. <b>(d, e)</b> Images obtained in a 79-year-old man who presented with jaundice. <b>(d)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneous ampullary lesion (arrow), with associated pancreatic and biliary duct dilatation. <b>(e)</b> Esophagogastroduodenoscopic biopsy findings confirmed the findings in d, and final pathologic analysis revealed villous adenoma involving the major and minor papillae.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig12b.jpeg" height="1128" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Duodenal villous lesions. <b>(a–c)</b> Images obtained in a 59-year-old man with epigastric pain. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a polypoid lesion (arrow) arising near the junction of the second and third portions of the duodenum. The lesion has a heterogeneous lobulated margin, with heterogeneous enhancement and surrounding fluid. The results of esophagogastroduodenoscopy <b>(b)</b> confirmed the findings in a, revealing a large lobulated tumor that was hypoechoic at endoscopic US <b>(c)</b>. Tissue-sampling results confirmed the presence of duodenal villous adenoma. <b>(d, e)</b> Images obtained in a 79-year-old man who presented with jaundice. <b>(d)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneous ampullary lesion (arrow), with associated pancreatic and biliary duct dilatation. <b>(e)</b> Esophagogastroduodenoscopic biopsy findings confirmed the findings in d, and final pathologic analysis revealed villous adenoma involving the major and minor papillae.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig12c.jpeg" height="1130" width="949" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. Duodenal villous lesions. <b>(a–c)</b> Images obtained in a 59-year-old man with epigastric pain. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a polypoid lesion (arrow) arising near the junction of the second and third portions of the duodenum. The lesion has a heterogeneous lobulated margin, with heterogeneous enhancement and surrounding fluid. The results of esophagogastroduodenoscopy <b>(b)</b> confirmed the findings in a, revealing a large lobulated tumor that was hypoechoic at endoscopic US <b>(c)</b>. Tissue-sampling results confirmed the presence of duodenal villous adenoma. <b>(d, e)</b> Images obtained in a 79-year-old man who presented with jaundice. <b>(d)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneous ampullary lesion (arrow), with associated pancreatic and biliary duct dilatation. <b>(e)</b> Esophagogastroduodenoscopic biopsy findings confirmed the findings in d, and final pathologic analysis revealed villous adenoma involving the major and minor papillae.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig12d.jpeg" height="929" width="1663" aria-labelledby="fig12d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12d</span>. Duodenal villous lesions. <b>(a–c)</b> Images obtained in a 59-year-old man with epigastric pain. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a polypoid lesion (arrow) arising near the junction of the second and third portions of the duodenum. The lesion has a heterogeneous lobulated margin, with heterogeneous enhancement and surrounding fluid. The results of esophagogastroduodenoscopy <b>(b)</b> confirmed the findings in a, revealing a large lobulated tumor that was hypoechoic at endoscopic US <b>(c)</b>. Tissue-sampling results confirmed the presence of duodenal villous adenoma. <b>(d, e)</b> Images obtained in a 79-year-old man who presented with jaundice. <b>(d)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneous ampullary lesion (arrow), with associated pancreatic and biliary duct dilatation. <b>(e)</b> Esophagogastroduodenoscopic biopsy findings confirmed the findings in d, and final pathologic analysis revealed villous adenoma involving the major and minor papillae.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig12d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig12e.jpeg" height="929" width="992" aria-labelledby="fig12e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12e</span>. Duodenal villous lesions. <b>(a–c)</b> Images obtained in a 59-year-old man with epigastric pain. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a polypoid lesion (arrow) arising near the junction of the second and third portions of the duodenum. The lesion has a heterogeneous lobulated margin, with heterogeneous enhancement and surrounding fluid. The results of esophagogastroduodenoscopy <b>(b)</b> confirmed the findings in a, revealing a large lobulated tumor that was hypoechoic at endoscopic US <b>(c)</b>. Tissue-sampling results confirmed the presence of duodenal villous adenoma. <b>(d, e)</b> Images obtained in a 79-year-old man who presented with jaundice. <b>(d)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneous ampullary lesion (arrow), with associated pancreatic and biliary duct dilatation. <b>(e)</b> Esophagogastroduodenoscopic biopsy findings confirmed the findings in d, and final pathologic analysis revealed villous adenoma involving the major and minor papillae.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig12e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig13a.jpeg" height="944" width="1013" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Rectal villous adenoma in a 53-year-old man found to have a large rectal mass at routine colorectal screening. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows a large lobulated lesion in the rectum. The lesion has intermediate signal intensity and is surrounded by rectal gel. At close inspection, a linear focus of high signal intensity (arrow), probably related to mucin coating, is present on the surface of the lesion. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows the lesion (arrow) with heterogeneous enhancement. <b>(c, d)</b> Diffusion-weighted <b>(c)</b> and apparent diffusion coefficient <b>(d)</b> MR images show the lesion (arrow) with restricted diffusion. <b>(e)</b> The mass was confirmed at colonoscopy. Endoscopic biopsy (not shown) revealed villous adenoma, although foci of invasive adenocarcinoma were identified at resection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig13b.jpeg" height="944" width="1074" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Rectal villous adenoma in a 53-year-old man found to have a large rectal mass at routine colorectal screening. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows a large lobulated lesion in the rectum. The lesion has intermediate signal intensity and is surrounded by rectal gel. At close inspection, a linear focus of high signal intensity (arrow), probably related to mucin coating, is present on the surface of the lesion. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows the lesion (arrow) with heterogeneous enhancement. <b>(c, d)</b> Diffusion-weighted <b>(c)</b> and apparent diffusion coefficient <b>(d)</b> MR images show the lesion (arrow) with restricted diffusion. <b>(e)</b> The mass was confirmed at colonoscopy. Endoscopic biopsy (not shown) revealed villous adenoma, although foci of invasive adenocarcinoma were identified at resection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig13c.jpeg" height="712" width="1571" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span>. Rectal villous adenoma in a 53-year-old man found to have a large rectal mass at routine colorectal screening. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows a large lobulated lesion in the rectum. The lesion has intermediate signal intensity and is surrounded by rectal gel. At close inspection, a linear focus of high signal intensity (arrow), probably related to mucin coating, is present on the surface of the lesion. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows the lesion (arrow) with heterogeneous enhancement. <b>(c, d)</b> Diffusion-weighted <b>(c)</b> and apparent diffusion coefficient <b>(d)</b> MR images show the lesion (arrow) with restricted diffusion. <b>(e)</b> The mass was confirmed at colonoscopy. Endoscopic biopsy (not shown) revealed villous adenoma, although foci of invasive adenocarcinoma were identified at resection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig13d.jpeg" height="712" width="1571" aria-labelledby="fig13d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13d</span>. Rectal villous adenoma in a 53-year-old man found to have a large rectal mass at routine colorectal screening. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows a large lobulated lesion in the rectum. The lesion has intermediate signal intensity and is surrounded by rectal gel. At close inspection, a linear focus of high signal intensity (arrow), probably related to mucin coating, is present on the surface of the lesion. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows the lesion (arrow) with heterogeneous enhancement. <b>(c, d)</b> Diffusion-weighted <b>(c)</b> and apparent diffusion coefficient <b>(d)</b> MR images show the lesion (arrow) with restricted diffusion. <b>(e)</b> The mass was confirmed at colonoscopy. Endoscopic biopsy (not shown) revealed villous adenoma, although foci of invasive adenocarcinoma were identified at resection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig13d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig13e.jpeg" height="944" width="1210" aria-labelledby="fig13e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13e</span>. Rectal villous adenoma in a 53-year-old man found to have a large rectal mass at routine colorectal screening. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows a large lobulated lesion in the rectum. The lesion has intermediate signal intensity and is surrounded by rectal gel. At close inspection, a linear focus of high signal intensity (arrow), probably related to mucin coating, is present on the surface of the lesion. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows the lesion (arrow) with heterogeneous enhancement. <b>(c, d)</b> Diffusion-weighted <b>(c)</b> and apparent diffusion coefficient <b>(d)</b> MR images show the lesion (arrow) with restricted diffusion. <b>(e)</b> The mass was confirmed at colonoscopy. Endoscopic biopsy (not shown) revealed villous adenoma, although foci of invasive adenocarcinoma were identified at resection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig13e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig14a.jpeg" height="1471" width="1350" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Rectal villous adenoma. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal T2-weighted <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced T1-weighted <b>(b)</b> MR images show a lobulated sessile rectal lesion (arrow) with relatively low T2 signal intensity and heterogeneous enhancement. <b>(c)</b> Endoscopic US image shows a lobulated hypoechoic mass (arrow) confined within the muscularis propria. <b>(d)</b> Endoscopic image shows a lobular lesion with a cerebriform surface pattern. Surgical pathology findings confirmed the presence of a villous adenoma with high-grade dysplasia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig14b.jpeg" height="1471" width="1314" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Rectal villous adenoma. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal T2-weighted <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced T1-weighted <b>(b)</b> MR images show a lobulated sessile rectal lesion (arrow) with relatively low T2 signal intensity and heterogeneous enhancement. <b>(c)</b> Endoscopic US image shows a lobulated hypoechoic mass (arrow) confined within the muscularis propria. <b>(d)</b> Endoscopic image shows a lobular lesion with a cerebriform surface pattern. Surgical pathology findings confirmed the presence of a villous adenoma with high-grade dysplasia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig14c.jpeg" height="1141" width="1275" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span>. Rectal villous adenoma. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal T2-weighted <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced T1-weighted <b>(b)</b> MR images show a lobulated sessile rectal lesion (arrow) with relatively low T2 signal intensity and heterogeneous enhancement. <b>(c)</b> Endoscopic US image shows a lobulated hypoechoic mass (arrow) confined within the muscularis propria. <b>(d)</b> Endoscopic image shows a lobular lesion with a cerebriform surface pattern. Surgical pathology findings confirmed the presence of a villous adenoma with high-grade dysplasia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig14d.jpeg" height="1141" width="1388" aria-labelledby="fig14d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14d</span>. Rectal villous adenoma. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal T2-weighted <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced T1-weighted <b>(b)</b> MR images show a lobulated sessile rectal lesion (arrow) with relatively low T2 signal intensity and heterogeneous enhancement. <b>(c)</b> Endoscopic US image shows a lobulated hypoechoic mass (arrow) confined within the muscularis propria. <b>(d)</b> Endoscopic image shows a lobular lesion with a cerebriform surface pattern. Surgical pathology findings confirmed the presence of a villous adenoma with high-grade dysplasia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig14d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig15a.jpeg" height="1251" width="1279" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Mucinous adenocarcinoma arising in a villous adenoma in a 48-year-old woman who presented with rectal bleeding and a mass. Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted fast spin-echo MR images show a large irregular T2-hyperintense cauliflower-like rectal mass, with invasion through its wall and extending into the presacral space (arrow in <b>a</b>). Note the underlying T2-hypointense frondlike mass (arrowhead in <b>b</b>) in the rectal lumen corresponding to the carpet rectal villous adenoma. Biopsy findings confirmed the presence of mucinous adenocarcinoma arising from a villous adenoma. Molecular analysis revealed <i>APC,</i> K-<i>ras, ATM,</i> and <i>TP53</i> mutations.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig15b.jpeg" height="1251" width="1171" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Mucinous adenocarcinoma arising in a villous adenoma in a 48-year-old woman who presented with rectal bleeding and a mass. Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted fast spin-echo MR images show a large irregular T2-hyperintense cauliflower-like rectal mass, with invasion through its wall and extending into the presacral space (arrow in <b>a</b>). Note the underlying T2-hypointense frondlike mass (arrowhead in <b>b</b>) in the rectal lumen corresponding to the carpet rectal villous adenoma. Biopsy findings confirmed the presence of mucinous adenocarcinoma arising from a villous adenoma. Molecular analysis revealed <i>APC,</i> K-<i>ras, ATM,</i> and <i>TP53</i> mutations.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig16a.jpeg" height="1285" width="1153" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. <b>(a)</b> Coronal T2-weighted single-shot fast spin-echo MR image shows an ampullary duodenal lesion with low signal intensity and associated biliary ductal dilatation (arrow). <b>(b)</b> The duodenal lesion (arrow) was confirmed at endoscopy. Biopsy revealed adenoma. Ampullary lesions can be challenging to detect and may mimic a normal or enlarged ampulla; however, the biliary ductal dilatation may be a signal that disease is present.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170159/asset/images/large/rg.2018170159.fig16b.jpeg" height="1285" width="1295" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. <b>(a)</b> Coronal T2-weighted single-shot fast spin-echo MR image shows an ampullary duodenal lesion with low signal intensity and associated biliary ductal dilatation (arrow). <b>(b)</b> The duodenal lesion (arrow) was confirmed at endoscopy. Biopsy revealed adenoma. Ampullary lesions can be challenging to detect and may mimic a normal or enlarged ampulla; however, the biliary ductal dilatation may be a signal that disease is present.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170159&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Vogelstein B, Fearon ER, Hamilton SR, et al. Genetic alterations during colorectal-tumor development. <em>N Engl J Med</em> 1988;319(9):525–532.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJM198809013190901">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/2841597/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Genetic+alterations+during+colorectal-tumor+development&amp;author=B+Vogelstein&amp;author=ER+Fearon&amp;author=SR+Hamilton&amp;publication_year=1988&amp;journal=N+Engl+J+Med&amp;pages=525-532&amp;doi=10.1056%2FNEJM198809013190901&amp;pmid=2841597">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class=